context: Shifts of international power have most notably occurred through major conflicts. The conclusion of the Great War and the resulting <a0_0><b4_0>treaties of Versailles, St-Germain, Neuilly, Trianon and Sèvres<b4_0/><a0_0/> witnessed the <a1_0>United Kingdom, France, Italy, Japan and the United States<a1_0/> as the chief arbiters of the new world order. <b6_0>In the aftermath of World War I<b6_0/> <b5_0>the German Empire<b5_0/> was defeated, the Austria-Hungarian empire was divided into new, less powerful states and the Russian Empire fell to a revolution. During the Paris Peace Conference, the "Big Four"—<a3_0><b7_0>France, Italy, United Kingdom and the United States<b7_0/><a3_0/>—held noticeably more power and influence on the proceedings and outcome of the treaties than Japan. The Big Four were leading architects of the Treaty of Versailles which was signed by Germany; the Treaty of St. Germain, with Austria; the Treaty of Neuilly, with Bulgaria; the Treaty of Trianon, with Hungary; and the Treaty of Sèvres, with the Ottoman Empire. During <b8_0>the decision-making of the Treaty of Versailles<b8_0/>, Italy pulled out of the conference because a part of its demands were not met and temporarily left the other three countries as the sole major architects of that treaty, referred to as the "<a2_0>Big Three<a2_0/>".
